  "prompt": "Whom was Muhammad worshipping before getting revelations?",
  "response": "Before receiving revelations, Muhammad, the founder of Islam, was not engaged in the worship of any deity in the manner prescribed by Islam. The pre-Islamic Arabian society was predominantly polytheistic, and the Kaaba in Mecca was a central shrine housing numerous idols representing various gods and goddesses worshipped by the local tribes.\n\nHistorical and Islamic sources indicate that Muhammad was known for his contemplative nature and inclination towards monotheistic thought. He would often retreat to the Cave of Hira, a few miles from Mecca, for meditation and reflection. This period of spiritual seclusion indicates a search for deeper meaning and truth, distinct from the prevailing polytheistic practices of his time.\n\nIslamic tradition holds that Muhammad was a hanif, a term used to describe someone who rejected idolatry and practiced a form of monotheism, even before the advent of Islam. The hanifs were considered to be followers of the pure monotheistic tradition of Abraham (Ibrahim in Islam). This aligns with the Islamic belief that Muhammad was inherently inclined towards the worship of the one true God (Allah in Arabic), even before the Quranic revelations began.\n\nIn essence, while Muhammad was not formally worshipping any specific deity in the ritualistic sense before the revelations, he was spiritually oriented towards a form of monotheistic belief, seeking a deeper understanding of the divine that was later fully articulated through the teachings of Islam.",
